        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "Lee, that takes real honesty to share — thank you. What you're describing sounds genuinely hard, and I want to make sure we give it the weight it deserves before we talk about training at all.\n\nHere's what I'm hearing: poor sleep all week, reduced appetite, dreading something you normally choose to do, and a resting HR running 8 bpm above your baseline. Those four things together are a meaningful signal from your body, not background noise. This pattern is consistent with what exercise scientists call functional overreaching — your system is telling you it needs more recovery than it's currently getting.\n\nI want to be straightforward with you about something, because I think you can handle it: **training hard on top of this won't get you to July faster. It's more likely to push you backward.** The adaptation you're chasing — the fitness gains — only happens during recovery, not during the runs themselves. Right now your body isn't recovering, which means the training stimulus isn't converting into fitness. You'd essentially be paying the cost without getting the benefit.\n\nBefore I say anything else about the plan — **what's your read on what's been driving the poor sleep?** Is this life stress, the training load itself, or something else? That matters a lot for figuring out the best path forward.\n\n---\n\nIn the meantime, here's what I'd suggest considering for this week, not as punishment but as a genuine investment in your July race:\n\n- **Drop volume by 30–40%** — shorter, easier runs only\n- **No quality work** (no threshold, no intervals) until the pattern breaks\n- **Easy pace means easy** — the slower end of 5:52–6:43/km, or even slower if that's what feels right\n\nAnd one more thing: **if the elevated HR, appetite loss, and sleep disruption continue beyond another week or two, I'd genuinely encourage you to check in with a doctor or sports medicine professional.** I can work with training load, but I'm not equipped to assess what's going on medically, and these symptoms can sometimes have causes worth ruling out.\n\nYou have 10 weeks. That is actually enough time — but only if we build on a foundation that's ready to be built on. A runner who arrives at the start line healthy and rested is in a far better position than one who's been grinding through warning signs for two months.\n\nWhat feels most realistic for you this week?"
        }
      ],
